# 3. Windows Boot Manager

File:

```
bootmgfw.efi
```

Location

```
EFI System Partition
```

Job

* Finds Windows installation
* Reads BCD
* Displays boot menu
* Starts Windows Loader

Think of Boot Manager as the receptionist.

It asks:

> Which operating system should I start?

---

# 4. BCD (Boot Configuration Data)

Think of BCD as a database.

It stores:

* Installed operating systems
* Boot menu timeout
* Safe Mode entries
* Recovery options
* Debug options

Location

```
EFI\Microsoft\Boot\BCD
```

or

```
\Boot\BCD
```

Useful Commands

```
bcdedit
```

Example

```
bcdedit /enum
```

---

# 5. winload.efi

This is the Windows Loader.

Job

Loads:

* Windows Kernel
* HAL
* Boot Drivers
* Registry Hive

Without it:

Windows cannot start.

Location

```
C:\Windows\System32\winload.efi
```

---

# 6. ntoskrnl.exe

This is the Windows Kernel.

The most important file in Windows.

Location

```
C:\Windows\System32\
```

Responsibilities

* Memory management
* Process scheduling
* Thread scheduling
* Driver communication
* Interrupt handling
* Virtual memory
* CPU scheduling

Think of it as the operating system's brain.

---

# 7. HAL (Hardware Abstraction Layer)

File

```
hal.dll
```

Purpose

Creates a common interface between Windows and hardware.

Without HAL:

Every motherboard would require a different Windows version.

HAL hides hardware differences.

Example

```
Application
     ↓
Windows
     ↓
HAL
     ↓
CPU
```

---

# 8. Session Manager (smss.exe)

First user-mode process created by the kernel.

Location

```
C:\Windows\System32\
```

Responsibilities

* Creates system session
* Creates user session
* Starts paging files
* Loads environment variables
* Starts csrss.exe
* Starts wininit.exe

Without it

Windows stops booting.

---

# 9. Winlogon

Process

```
winlogon.exe
```

Responsibilities

* Shows login screen
* Ctrl+Alt+Delete
* Starts user shell
* Loads user profile
* Handles lock/unlock
* Password changes

Without Winlogon

No login screen appears.

---

# 10. LSASS

Process

```
lsass.exe
```

Local Security Authority Subsystem Service

Responsibilities

* Authenticates users
* Creates security tokens
* Enforces password policy
* Kerberos authentication
* NTLM authentication
* Domain authentication
* Auditing

Example

When you log in to an Active Directory domain:

```
Username
Password
      ↓
Winlogon
      ↓
LSASS
      ↓
Domain Controller
      ↓
Success
```

If `lsass.exe` crashes, Windows typically forces a restart because it cannot maintain system security.

---

# 11. Explorer.exe

This is the Windows Shell.

Starts after successful login.

Responsibilities

* Desktop
* Taskbar
* Start Menu
* File Explorer
* Icons

Location

```
C:\Windows\explorer.exe
```

Without Explorer

Windows still runs, but you only see a command prompt or Task Manager (depending on how the shell is started).

